The rain always smelled like rusted metal. It coated everything – the porch swing, the window pane, even the inside of my lungs. Grey. Everything was grey. I’d stopped trying to paint it, stopped trying to shift the hues, stopped trying to make it feel *anything* other than the dull, persistent ache in my bones.

The kettle hissed, a tiny, insistent protest against the silence. I hadn’t touched it in days. Not really. It was a habit, a ritual. A pointless, comforting gesture. The rhythmic *hiss* was a miniature echo of the emptiness inside.

My apartment was a mausoleum of half-finished projects. A half-knitted scarf lay draped across the armchair, a collection of seashells gathered on the beach, and a sketchbook filled with mostly blank pages. I’d started sketching again, years ago, a desperate attempt to capture the sharpness of a memory, a feeling of… something. Now, the shapes just blurred, didn't they? Like looking at a watercolor washed in a storm.

The mailman shuffled past, his footsteps muffled by the wet pavement. He offered a brief, impersonal wave. I didn’t look up. Didn’t want to acknowledge the weight pressing down, a constant, slow erosion.  I’d lost track of how many days it had been. Days bled into one another, punctuated only by the rain and the gnawing hollowness. 

A single robin landed on the sill, tilting its head, then flitting away with a quick, almost frantic movement. It reminded me of… of something. A fleeting, impossible connection. I watched it, wanting to reach out, but the hand I held remained stubbornly still. 

The silence was thick, a tangible thing. It pressed against me, a heavy blanket woven with the scent of rain and regret. I sat on the edge of the sofa, my feet dangling.  I traced the outline of a chipped teacup with my finger, the porcelain cool and smooth beneath my touch. A forgotten joy, a ghost of warmth, lingered. 

There was a system, a meticulously constructed wall of avoidance.  It wasn't an effort to shut out the world; it was a refusal to engage. A way to protect myself from the sharp edges of feeling.  It felt… exhausting. Like pulling teeth to extract a single drop of water.

I considered the books on the shelf – stacks of well-worn paperbacks, each promising a different destination.  I’d read them all, or rather, I’d felt the urge to, then the inevitable retreat. The words felt brittle, hollow. 

The rain intensified, drumming against the window.  I closed my eyes, the metallic scent filling my nostrils.  A small, faded photograph lay on the floor beside me – a picture of my brother, grinning, holding a brightly colored kite.  It wasn't a painful image, not exactly. It was a reminder of laughter, of boundless possibility.  I reached for it, then pulled my hand back.  It was just a picture.